d, keep one Machine running.\n-\n-Good alternates:\n-\n-- Render background worker or private service + persistent disk. Render supports\n-  disks for paid services and background workers, but disks disable\n-  zero-downtime deploys. That is acceptable for v1 if the generator API handles\n-  retryable busy/down states\n-  ([Render disks](https://render.com/docs/disks),\n-  [Render deploys](https://render.com/docs/deploys)).\n-- Railway service + volume. Railway volumes mount persistent read/write storage\n-  into a service; replicas cannot be used with volumes, which again fits the\n-  one-writer model\n-  ([Railway volumes](https://docs.railway.com/volumes),\n-  [Railway volume reference](https://docs.railway.com/reference/volumes)).\n-\n-AWS path if needed:\n-\n-- If the team already has AWS infrastructure and wants to avoid another\n-  platform, use **one EC2 instance + one EBS data volume** for v1. This is the\n-  AWS equivalent of the Fly Machine + Volume shape: one app, one block device,\n-  one writer.\n+Recommended AWS hosting path:\n+\n+- Use **one EC2 instance + one EBS data volume** for v1. This is one app, one\n+  block device, one writer.\n - Run the Agent Trail app in Docker or systemd on the instance. Install `git` in\n   the image or host package set. Mount the EBS volume at `/data` or\n   `/var/lib/agent-trail`.\n@@\n - Lambda + EFS and ECS + EFS can work technically, but they introduce VPC, mount\n   targets, IAM, throughput modes, network filesystem semantics, and more\n   operational surface. Use them only if the product is already committed to AWS\n   ([Lambda EFS](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html),\n   [ECS EFS](https://docs.aws.amazon.[REDACTED:entropy].html)).\n+\n+Non-AWS alternates if AWS turns out to be painful:\n+\n+- Fly.io Machine + Fly Volume\n+  ([Fly volumes](https://fly.io/docs/volumes/overview/)).\n+- Render persistent disk\n+  ([Render disks](https://render.com/docs/disks)).\n+- Railway volume\n+  ([Railway volumes]